Explain the following compiler error:

Error:
& has lower precedence than ==; == will be evaluated first [-wparentheses]

Code:
2: int main() {
3:     int cond = 1;
4:     if (cond & cond == 1) {}
5:     return 0;
6: }
,"The compiler is reporting that you used '&' (bitwise) where you likely meant '&&' (logical). Bitwise operators look at individual bits (microscopic level), while logical operators look at true/false values (macroscopic level). For 'if' statements, you almost always want '&&'."

Explain the following compiler error:

Error:
duplicate case value '1'

Code:
6:         case 1:
7:             printf("one");
8:         case 1:
9:             printf("one again");
10:             break;
,This error indicates that two case labels in the switch statement have the same value. The compiler can't decide which case to execute when that value matches. It's like having two doors with the same number—the program won't know which one to open.

